"The text you provided is about the design and implementation of a module called ADPM (Adaptive Dynamic Personalization Module) for Etsy Ads. The module is used to personalize sponsored search's CTR (Click-Through Rate) and PCCVR (Product Click-Through Rate) models by concatenating the short-term dynamic user representation from ADPM to the input representation layer. Here's a summary of its components:1. Component One: This component introduces representations for each sequence from scratch in its own vector space as part of the downstream models. It learns lightweight representations for many different (entity, action) sequences for which we do not have pretrained representations.2. Component Two: This component encodes sequences using listing ID pretrained representations together with average pooling. Depending on downstream performance and availability, it can use multimodal (AIR) representations, visual representations, or interaction-based representations.3. Component Three: The third component of the ADPM is a general plug-and-play module that can be easily scaled to multiple downstream personalization tasks while at the same time introducing a per-model customization to avoid sacrificing performance. It is designed as a TensorFlow Keras layer, which can be reused across personalization use-cases with a simple import statement.2.7.1 Vocabularies: ADPM's sequence representations are implemented as lookup tables. However, when vocabularies are large, the corresponding weight matrices can take up too much memory and disk space, a significant challenge in deployments. To overcome this challenge and reduce memory consumption, the vocabulary size for each sequence is limited to the top most frequent entities, tuning this as a hyperparameter in downstream CTR and PCCVR models. For example, the CTR's vocabulary corresponding to sequences of listing IDs was capped to top 750,000 listings, down from 100 million in total.": "The text you provided discusses the Adaptive Dynamic Personalization Module (ADPM) used by Etsy Ads to personalize sponsored search's Click-Through Rate (CTR) and Product Click-Through Rate (PCCVR) models. The ADPM consists of three components: 1) Component One learns representations for each sequence from scratch in its own vector space as part of the downstream models, 2) Component Two encodes sequences using listing ID pretrained representations together with average pooling, and 3) Component Three is a general plug-and-play module that can be easily scaled to multiple downstream personalization tasks. The ADPM is implemented as a TensorFlow Keras layer and uses lookup tables for sequence representations, but limits the vocabulary size for each sequence to the top most frequent entities to reduce memory consumption."
}

{
"paper_title": "Retrieval-Augmented Generation with Knowledge Graphs for Customer Service Question Answering",
"authors": ["Author 1", "Author 2"],
"abstract": "This paper presents a framework that combines retrieval-augmented generation and knowledge graphs to address customer service questions. The approach involves constructing a knowledge graph from historical issue tickets, generating embeddings for node values, and using an embedding-based retrieval system to filter relevant sub-graphs based on user queries. The paper also describes a method for entity identification and intent detection in user queries, which is used to guide the retrieval process. The framework demonstrates notable flexibility in accommodating varied query formulations by leveraging the LLM's extensive understanding and interpretive capabilities.",
"introduction": "The paper introduces a novel approach for answering customer service questions using a combination of retrieval-augmented generation and knowledge graphs. The proposed framework aims to improve the efficiency and effectiveness of customer service systems by leveraging historical issue tickets to construct a knowledge graph, generating embeddings for node values, and using an embedding-based retrieval system to filter relevant sub-graphs based on user queries.",
"methodology": {
"knowledge_graph_construction": "The construction of the knowledge graph involves parsing each issue ticket into a tree representation, identifying inter-ticket connections, generating embeddings for node values, and storing the graph in a database. The process is guided by a predefined graph template.",
"embedding_generation": "Embeddings are generated for node values using pre-trained text-embedding models like BERT and E5, specifically targeting nodes for text-rich sections such as 'issue summary', 'issue description', and 'steps to reproduce', etc.",
"retrieval_and_question_answering": "The retrieval process involves extracting pertinent sub-graphs from the knowledge graph, aligned with user-provided specifics such as 'issue description' and 'issue summary', as well as user intentions like 'fix solution'. This process consists of two primary steps: EBR-based ticket identification and LLM-driven subgraph extraction."
},
"results": "The paper presents preliminary results demonstrating the effectiveness of the proposed framework in answering customer service questions. The approach was able to accurately identify relevant historical issue tickets, extract pertinent sub-graphs, and generate accurate answers using the LLM.",
"conclusion": "In conclusion, this paper presents a novel approach for addressing customer service questions using retrieval-augmented generation and knowledge graphs. The proposed framework demonstrates notable flexibility in accommodating varied query formulations by leveraging the LLM's extensive understanding and interpretive capabilities. Future work includes further evaluation of the approach on larger datasets and integration with real-world customer service systems."
}

