        "text": "Title: Designing and Shipping a New Feature at DoorDash: A Focus on Practices, Unique Characteristics, and Benefits\n\nAt DoorDash, we pride ourselves on our ability to design and ship new features that not only improve the efficiency of our operations but also enhance the user experience. In this blog post, we'll delve into the practices, unique work characteristics, and benefits of our approach.\n\nStarting Simple: One of the key practices we follow is starting simple. This means breaking down complex problems into manageable milestones and working iteratively. By doing so, we can quickly ship a minimum viable product (MVP) that delivers immediate value while also providing a foundation for further development.\n\nBreaking it Down: Another important practice is breaking the problem down into smaller, more manageable parts. This allows us to focus on specific aspects of the feature and ensures that each part is thoroughly tested and refined before moving on to the next. This approach also enables us to assemble a team around great ideas, fostering collaboration and ensuring that everyone is aligned with the project's goals.\n\nBias for Action: We operate with a strong bias for action. This means we are not afraid to ship features that may not be perfect but can still deliver immediate value. This approach encourages experimentation and helps us quickly iterate on our solutions based on real-world feedback.\n\nUnique Work Characteristics: One of the unique work characteristics at DoorDash is our ability to construct teams around great ideas. This bottom-up approach allows us to bring together individuals with diverse skills and expertise, fostering collaboration and ensuring that we have the right people working on the right problems.\n\nProviding Incremental Results: Another unique characteristic is our focus on providing incremental results. By delivering value early and often, we can gain time and buy-in from stakeholders, making it easier to invest in longer-term projects that may carry more risk.\n\nBuilding Necessary Tooling: To support the feature as it grows, we also focus on building necessary tooling for operations, debugging, and rapid experimentation. This ensures that our teams have the tools they need to effectively develop and maintain their features over time.\n\nConclusion: Our approach to designing and shipping new features at DoorDash is rooted in a few key practices: starting simple, breaking it down, bias for action, constructing teams around great ideas, providing incremental results, and building necessary tooling. By following these practices, we can deliver value quickly while also setting the stage for long-term success.\n\nAbout the Authors:\nRita Golovonevsky is a Machine Learning Science Engineer at DoorDash, focusing on enhancing assignment decision algorithms using ML. Ram Tripathi is a Software Engineer at DoorDash, focusing on enhancing efficiency and order accuracy."
