      "In this article, the Hubble team at Grab shares their journey of improving data discovery using AI and LLMs (Large Language Models). They have made significant progress in enhancing search capabilities, increasing documentation coverage, and reducing the time taken for data discovery. \n\nThe first step was to enhance Elasticsearch by tagging and boosting P80 tables, boosting relevant schemas, hiding irrelevant datasets, debooosting deprecated tables, improving the search UI, adding relevant tags, and boosting certified tables. This resulted in a 12 percentage point increase in click-through rate.\n\nThe second step was to build a Context Store for HubbleIQ, which uses GPT-4 to generate documentation based on table schemas and sample data. The team added a 'generate' button on the Hubble UI, allowing data producers to easily generate documentation for their tables. They also pre-populated docs for critical tables and notified data producers to review the generated documentation.\n\nThe third step was to build and launch HubbleIQ, which is an LLM with a custom system prompt that can access all Hubble datasets catalogued on Glean. It was integrated into Hubble search, such that for any search that is likely to be a semantic search, HubbleIQ results are shown on top, followed by regular search results. Recently, they integrated HubbleIQ with Slack, allowing data consumers to discover datasets without breaking their flow.\n\nThe impact of these improvements was significant. A follow-up survey revealed that 73% of respondents found it easy to discover datasets, marking a substantial 17 percentage point increase from the previous survey. Moreover, Hubble reached an all-time high in monthly active users, demonstrating the effectiveness of the enhancements made to the platform.\n\nNext steps include enriching the documentation generator with more context, streamlining the process by allowing analysts to auto-update data docs based on Slack threads directly from Slack, developing an evaluator model that leverages LLMs to assess the quality of both human and AI-written docs, and implementing Reflexion, an agentic workflow that utilizes the outputs from the doc evaluator to iteratively regenerate docs until a quality benchmark is met or a maximum try-limit is reached.\n\nFor HubbleIQ, the focus will be on continuous improvement. They have already added support for metric datasets and are actively working on incorporating other types of datasets as well. To provide a more seamless user experience, they will enable users to ask follow-up questions to HubbleIQ directly on the HubbleUI, with the system intelligently pulling additional metadata when a user mentions a specific dataset.\n\nIn conclusion, the Hubble team is confident that they will continue to make substantial progress in the right direction over the next few production cycles. They invite readers to join them on this exciting journey of data discovery revolution."
