  "response": "The process of creating activity embeddings for job recommendations on LinkedIn involves several steps. First, a sequence of job embeddings is created for each member based on their job activity history. This sequence includes the job embeddings concatenated with their three-dimensional one-hot label (APPLY/SAVE/DISMISS), ordered by ascending timestamp. \n\nNext, sequence-based deep learning models such as LSTM, CNN, or Transformer are used as the aggregation function to learn a complex aggregation function over the job embedding sequence. To train these models, a proxy training task is needed. LinkedIn proposed a model where for a member with n activities in the last 28 days, they feed in as input to their sequence model the first n-1 activities concatenated with their one-hot label, and hold out the last (job embedding, label) pair. They enforce it to be the same size as the input job embedding, because now they use the job embedding they held out and apply a Hadamard (pointwise) product, followed by a fully-connected layer and softmax to predict whether the held out action was positive (APPLY/SAVE) or negative (DISMISS). This gives them a standard classification task with cross-entropy loss to train the sequence model weights. \n\nAfter training, the Tensorflow sub-model is packaged and used for embedding precomputation. A regularly scheduled inference pipeline publishes the pre-computed activity embeddings for each member to their Feature Marketplace for consumption by other AI models (e.g., JYMBII) during both offline training and online inference. The activity embeddings are updated often to give the most relevant results."
