    "title": "Graph Technologies in Fraud Detection and Prevention at PayPal",
    "text": "In this case study, we will discuss the use of graph technologies for fraud detection and prevention at PayPal. 

1. Real-time Graph Compute: PayPal's graph platform has a real-time graph compute capability that allows for relationship queries to be completed within sub-seconds. This is crucial in detecting and preventing fraudulent activities, as many connections are already stored in the graph platform.

2. Graph Viewer: The graph viewer provides an intuitive way for team members to inspect and investigate connections between two accounts through their profile assets or digital fingerprint like IP address, etc. This makes it easier for risk teammates to identify any relationships and spot fraud rings.

3. Generating Graph Embeddings with Mirror Graph: To learn embeddings or representations directly on graphs depicted by the buyer-seller ecosystems at PayPal, a mirror graph capability is used that allows scalable generation of multi-hop neighborhoods for large graph-based networks. This is then used to generate node embeddings.

4. Case Study: Repeat Fraudsters Pattern: By using the real-time graph, PayPal can link newly added accounts to existing bad actors in near real-time and prevent potential damage. This is particularly useful in detecting and preventing fraud patterns from actors with malicious intent that are sporadic, ever-evolving, and rapidly reactive.

5. Benefits: The benefits of using graph technologies for fraud detection and prevention at PayPal include easier relationship queries, intuitive visualization for investigation, and the ability to quickly identify relationships and spot fraud rings."
  }
}

