{
"model": "stuff",
"data": {
"document": {
"type": "article",
"name": "You-are-a-pig-Detecting-speakers-without-facial-recognition-in-video-transcripts",
"url": "https://medium.com/swlh/you-are-a-pig-detecting-speakers-without-facial-recognition-in-video-transcripts-3e684f5c712d",
"title": "You’re a Pig: Detecting Speakers Without Facial Recognition in Video Transcripts",
"summary": "In this article, we discuss how to detect speakers without facial recognition in video transcripts. We focus on identifying and isolating speaker transitions and extracting the names of speakers from these transitions.",
"license": "CC BY-NC-SA 4.0",
"source": "Medium",
"author": "Alon Faktor",
"date_published": "2021-03-25T16:00:00Z",
"eleven_blocks": [
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "In this article, we discuss how to detect speakers without facial recognition in video transcripts. We focus on identifying and isolating speaker transitions and extracting the names of speakers from these transitions."
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "The goal is to convert the unstructured transcript into a structured dialog that includes the names of the speakers."
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Within the context of answering questions, particularly in knowledge-sharing videos through formats such as corporate or sales meetings, questions are often aimed at particular speakers. However, we can’t refer to auxiliary sources to access name data for these speakers."
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Consider the following example from The Lion King (1994), where Pumbaa, a warthog, says, ‘I ate like a pig,’ to which the lion king Simba replies, ‘Pumbaa, you are a pig.’"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "The goal is to convert the unstructured transcript into a structured dialog that includes the names of the speakers."
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Our research shows that the most common place to find the names of speakers in conversational videos is during conversation transitions from one person to another. These transitions, characterized by the handover of conversational turns between participants, hold a lot of name data."
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "For example, if you look at the conversation transition between Pumbaa and Simba, you can see that Simba is referring to Pumbaa by name, so it’s possible to conclude the name of the first speaker:"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Pumbaa: ‘I ate like a pig.’"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Speaker 2: ‘Pumbaa, you are a pig.’"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Note that you can disregard or mask Pumbaa’s statement without affecting name identification:"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Pumbaa: [ — — — ]"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Speaker 2: ‘Pumbaa, you are a pig.’"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "This is just one of the prompts that we use to get several name votes for each speaker ID."
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "We also ask for an identification based on all transitions attributed to a single speaker. Each identification corresponds to one vote. We then apply a decision function to remove any errors in the voting in aggregate and determine if the speaker’s name corresponding to the numerical ID can be established with a high level of confidence."
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "If you look closely at Figure 4, you see that we use four different prompts to get several name votes for each speaker ID. The first prompt asks if the LLM can identify the name of Speaker 2 from what Speaker 1 just said, like this:"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Speaker 1: ‘Take it away, Rachel.’"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Speaker 2: [ — — — ]"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "The second prompt asks if the LLM can identify the name of Speaker 1 from what Speaker 2 says immediately afterward, like this:"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Speaker 1: [ — — — ]"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Speaker 2: ‘Thanks, David.’"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "That’s the pattern that gives us Pumbaa’s name."
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "The third prompt asks the LLM if the speaker is giving a self-introduction:"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Speaker 2: ‘Hi, everyone, great to be here. My name is Rachel.’"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "The fourth prompt asks the LLM to identify the name of a specific speaker by passing all transitions of this speaker at once. That’s how to determine Simba’s name, which the LLM can’t ascertain from what either Pumbaa or Simba says in the current context. But Simba’s name does come up in a different context earlier and later in the movie:"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Speaker 2: ‘Whoa! Nice one, Simba.’"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Speaker 1: ‘Thanks. Man, I’m stuffed.’"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Speaker 3: ‘Me too. I ate like a pig.’"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Speaker 1: ‘Pumbaa, you are a pig.’"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Speaker 3: ‘Simba, what do you think?’"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Speaker 1: ‘Well, I don’t know.’"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "So from these transitions of Speaker 1, the LLM can deduce that Speaker 1 is actually Simba."
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "We have now yielded a structured transcript:"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Pumbaa: ‘I ate like a pig.’"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Simba: ‘Pumbaa, you are a pig.’"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Finding accurate reference points in the video"
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Since we’re dealing with videos, there’s significant value in not only answering the question in a textual fashion but also referring the viewer to watch moments in the video that support the answer (see Figure 5). These playable moments can convey additional information that doesn’t necessarily appear in the textual answer, including details that were left out, but also visual information, tone of voice, music, emotions, and other potentially relevant factors."
},
{
"type": "paragraph",
"content": "Press enter to see more."
}
]
}
}
}

