"query": {
"children": [
{
"name": "h1",
"arguments": {},
"value": "Email Classification System: Designing an Eventual Consistent Data Model for Predicting Email Types in Context to Your Team"
},
{
"name": "p",
"arguments": {},
"value": "By designing an eventually-consistent data model, we were able to roll out the email classification feature without backfills and with real-time data updates to provide a highly accurate data model for predicting email types in context to your team."
},
{
"name": "h2",
"arguments": {},
"value": "Introduction"
},
{
"name": "p",
"arguments": {},
"value": "To provide smart suggestions to our end-users, we developed a classification engine that can determine if an email address is internal or external. To support this, we need a near real-time representation of the total number of users each team has grouped by domain and role."
},
{
"name": "h2",
"arguments": {},
"value": "Backfilling Data"
},
{
"name": "p",
"arguments": {},
"value": "A backfill to perform aggregation for millions of users would have been too expensive to execute on a daily basis. By designing an eventually-consistent data model, we were able to avoid the need for backfills."
},
{
"name": "h2",
"arguments": {},
"value": "Data Model Design"
},
{
"name": "p",
"arguments": {},
"value": "To design an eventually-consistent data model, we made the following tradeoffs:"
},
{
"name": "ul",
"arguments": {},
"children": [
{
"name": "li",
"arguments": {},
"value": "Reduced accuracy in exchange for faster performance."
},
{
"name": "li",
"arguments": {},
"value": "Accepting some data drift and using a self-healing system to fix it."
}
]
},
{
"name": "h2",
"arguments": {},
"value": "Data Model Schema"
},
{
"name": "p",
"arguments": {},
"value": "The data model schema consists of the following tables:"
},
{
"name": "ul",
"arguments": {},
"children": [
{
"name": "li",
"arguments": {},
"value": "teams: Stores information about each team, including the total number of users and the number of users grouped by domain and role."
},
{
"name": "li",
"arguments": {},
"value": "users: Stores information about each user, including their email address, domain, and role."
}
]
},
{
"name": "h2",
"arguments": {},
"value": "Data Model Implementation"
},
{
"name": "p",
"arguments": {},
"value": "The data model is implemented using a combination of SQL and asynchronous job queues. When a new user joins a team, their information is added to the users table. The total number of users for each team is calculated by querying the users table and aggregating the results."
},
{
"name": "h2",
"arguments": {},
"value": "Self-Healing System"
},
{
"name": "p",
"arguments": {},
"value": "To prevent data drift, we've built a self-healing system that calculates the current drift and applies the appropriate operations to realign the counts. The healer has the following five distinct phases:"
},
{
"name": "ul",
"arguments": {},
"children": [
{
"name": "li",
"arguments": {},
"value": "Fetch all current domain counts for the team."
},
{
"name": "li",
"arguments": {},
"value": "Iterate through all users of the team and do a second in-memory count."
},
{
"name": "li",
"arguments": {},
"value": "Compare the in-memory counts to the current domain counts."
},
{
"name": "li",
"arguments": {},
"value": "Calculate the operations needed to align the two sets."
},
{
"name": "li",
"arguments": {},
"value": "Apply the operations with the same UPSERT queries as our mutations."
}
]
},
{
"name": "h2",
"arguments": {},
"value": "Conclusion"
},
{
"name": "p",
"arguments": {},
"value": "By connecting the classification engine to our existing tokenizer, we can now determine whether a given email address belongs to someone who is part of your organization (highlighted below) or to someone external (shown as a paper plane). The email classification provides predictions whether each provided email is internal or external."
},
{
"name": "h2",
"arguments": {},
"value": "Closing Notes"
},
{
"name": "p",
"arguments": {},
"value": "Designing real-time data models that can scale is hard. In this post, we covered an eventual consistent system that leverages thresholds to do smart predictions. Often, tradeoffs need to be made and in our use-case, we allow reduced accuracy in exchange for faster performance. We've just scratched the surface of email classification, and we're excited to see what we'll be able to do next with deep learning! If you like designing architecture, data models, and async service, come join us!"
}
]
},
