{
"document": {
"type": "article",
"name": "Advanced Prompting Techniques for Large Language Models",
"heading": "Introduction",
"paragraphs": [
{
"content": "This article discusses advanced prompting techniques that can be used to improve the performance and effectiveness of large language models like me. These techniques are based on treating the model as a human participant, encouraging it to think more deeply about its responses, and using multiple rounds of prompting to apply various techniques."
}
]
},
"conversation": {
"speaker": "Assistant",
"content": "Let's dive into some advanced prompting techniques that we've developed at Instacart. We don't claim to be the only ones to come up with these, but we have used all of these in developing the Ava family of products that we use for internal workflows."
},
"conversation": {
"speaker": "Assistant",
"content": "First, let's talk about Room for Thought — Make a Plan First. This technique is about explicitly encouraging the LLM to make a plan before starting to answer the question. This can be a pretty delicate balance of picking the right word."
},
"conversation": {
"speaker": "Assistant",
"content": "Here's an example of how Room for Thought might work: First let's create an outline for the pull request description. Do not generate a title and description, only write the outline. Be sure to think about what the categories of the change are (i.e. 1. A change to add the --foo argument, 2. Add retries for network calls, etc) based on what you see in the diff."
},
"conversation": {
"speaker": "Assistant",
"content": "By giving the model room to think about how to best compose the pull request, we're allowing it to make mistakes, try different approaches, and only then create the output. This gives the model more time to consider the problem and come up with a better solution."
},
"conversation": {
"speaker": "Assistant",
"content": "Next, let's discuss Monte Carlo — Brainstorm Options. In the Monte Carlo technique, we ask the model to generate several different options, and then use those options to create a final answer that brings the best aspects of all of the generated answers."
},
"conversation": {
"speaker": "Assistant",
"content": "Here's an example of how Monte Carlo might work: I am looking for ideas for my 9 year old's birthday party. She is into Pokemon, corgis, Roblox, and loves playing with her friends."
},
"conversation": {
"speaker": "Assistant",
"content": "First list out elements of a good birthday party for a kid that can be accomplished on a budget, and a list of fun themes/ elements of a party given her interests. Then create 5 radically different ideas for parties. Finally create a final singular title recommendation that combines the best elements of the options."
},
"conversation": {
"speaker": "Assistant",
"content": "The best part of Monte Carlo is when you are doing it interactively, you get 5 additional options as part of the generation. Often I find one of the options in the list appeals to me, and I pick it."
},
"conversation": {
"speaker": "Assistant",
